Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 121st Weekly Dose of Optimism. Bit of =
a return to normal this week: no election buildup and less election fallout=
=2E And a normal week is generally a=
 pretty good week, if you=E2=80=99re payi=
ng attention. History-making rocket launches, breakthroughs in quantum mech=
anics, drug discoveries, and, yes, a dose of optimistic political news.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
(1) SpaceX Starship launches banana to space, skips giant rocket catch on 6=
th test flight [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6ba8944-b584-4ed6-a484-5db1=
4c43b126?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]
Mike Wall for Space
Today's mission aimed to do far more than just bring Super Heavy back to Ea=
rth [ https://substack.com/redirect/6b6e838a-bba8-45bc-bd1f-67b49283e75b?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in one =
piece. SpaceX also wanted to put Starship's upper stage =E2=80=94 a 165-foo=
t-tall (50 m) spacecraft called Starship, or simply "Ship" =E2=80=94 throug=
h its paces.
It was just another day at SpaceX this week, when the company successfully =
completed its sixth launch of Starship. While flight data did not indicate =
a chopstick-catch landing was possible, the launch was still successful in =
all other regards.
The mission successfully tested Starship's reentry capabilities, including =
modifications to its heat shield and engine relight in microgravity, while =
also achieving a controlled splashdown of both stages. These advancements a=
re critical for developing a fully reusable spacecraft capable of supportin=
g lunar landings, Mars missions, and whatever other civilization-altering m=
issions the company has planned.
It=E2=80=99s amazing that the company has turned launching and safely landi=
ng Starships into an almost common occurrence in such a short amount of tim=
e. As a reminder, Starship is over 400 feet tall, is the largest and most p=
owerful rocket ever built, and dwarfs the Statue of Liberty. We can now lau=
nch the Statue of Liberty into space and land it safely back on earth, and =
it=E2=80=99s not even a big news story anymore.
Elon is on an all-time heater. We simply must just let this man cook.
(2) Javier Milei: President of Argentina - Freedom, Economics, and Corrupti=
on | Lex Fridman Podcast #453 [ https://substack.com/redirect/6588e801-9371=
-45a0-99a6-3080348da9a2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Lex Fridman Podcast
Speaking of just letting people cook, President Javier Milei went on Lex=E2=
=80=99s podcast this week and explained just what he=E2=80=99s been up to i=
n Argentina over the past year. His aggressive austerity measures have deli=
vered astounding results: achieving a fiscal surplus for the first time in =
over a decade and reducing monthly inflation to below 3%, the lowest in thr=
ee years. His administration has already removed or significantly amended o=
ver 300 regulations, and now alters around five regulations per day with th=
e goal of making changes to over 4,000 laws. You may not like his style, bu=
t the results speak for themselves.
You may be asking yourself, =E2=80=9CWhy should I care about what the Presi=
dent of Argentina is up to?=E2=80=9D The answer is pretty clear: Milei=E2=
=80=99s approach to government efficiency and deregulation is serving as th=
e playbook for the US Government=E2=80=99s forthcoming Department of Govern=
ment Efficiency (DOGE.) Don=E2=80=99t take my word for it =E2=80=94 both Mu=
sk and Milei are on record stating as much. Yesterday, Elon tweeted a video=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/2798526a-c1d7-40a5-a9fa-cb812dc76742?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of Milton F=
riedman doing the video version of Leonard Read=E2=80=99s I, Pencil [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/eced925c-ca27-4883-bccf-00c895f05d25?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
Beyond our shared enthusiasm for governmental efficiency, three other thing=
s stood out to me from this conversation.
It=E2=80=99s super refreshing to hear from a politician that is extremely w=
ell-versed in economics and doesn=E2=80=99t talk strictly in platitudes whe=
n it comes to the economy. Even if you don=E2=80=99t agree with all of his =
conclusions, you=E2=80=99d likely agree that he is well read.
Milei does about as good of a job as anyone explaining the origins and dang=
ers of wokeness. His analysis is not inflammatory and doesn=E2=80=99t simpl=
y cherry pick examples from =E2=80=98Libs of TikTok=E2=80=99, but rather, i=
t is rooted in a deep understanding of the history and philosophy of social=
ism.
ElevenLabs [ https://substack.com/redirect/2236d5db-11b5-4ead-9474-77413407=
1862?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] i=
s sweet. The original conversation occurred between an English speaking Lex=
, a Spanish speaking Milei, and an interpreter. But the podcast was present=
ed using an overdub from ElevenLabs that made it sound like a fully English=
 conversation between Lex and Milei. It was a very high-quality overdub and=
, if Lex had not broken it down at the beginning of the podcast, I am not s=
ure I would=E2=80=99ve picked up that Milei=E2=80=99s voice was AI-generate=
d.
(3) A mechanical qubit [ https://substack.com/redirect/9e1d4d9c-0df7-4d6b-b=
901-c4834788fcc5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]
Yang et al in Science
By coupling a bulk acoustic wave resonator to a superconducting qubit, the =
authors engineered a parameter regime in which a mechanical mode of the res=
onator inherits the nonlinear features of the superconducting qubit necessa=
ry for strong phonon-phonon interactions. They then demonstrated a full set=
 of single-qubit operations on their mechanical qubit.
Researchers have created a new type of qubit using mechanical vibrations, c=
alled a mechanical qubit, by coupling a resonator to a superconducting qubi=
t. As a reminder, a qubit is the fundamental unit of quantum information, c=
apable of existing in multiple states simultaneously (superposition) for ad=
vanced computing and information processing.=20
The mechanical qubit allowed them to engineer strong interactions between p=
honons (quantized sound waves) at the single-quantum level, something previ=
ously impossible in mechanical systems. They demonstrated full control of t=
he qubit, including initialization and quantum gates, with the system showi=
ng remarkably long quantum lifetimes.=20
If you didn=E2=80=99t understand that, you=E2=80=99re not alone =E2=80=94 h=
ere=E2=80=99s why it matters: the breakthrough opens the door to using quan=
tum sound for advanced technologies like highly sensitive sensors, powerful=
 simulations, and efficient quantum computers. It=E2=80=99s a leap toward m=
aking quantum acoustics a key player in the future of quantum technology.
Separately, researchers showed that AI outperforms humans in quantum error =
correction [ https://substack.com/redirect/9cfbcc31-d88d-4499-b145-56079fab=
67ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=
=20
Progress in quantum is accelerating. It feels like this is another =E2=80=
=9Calways-a-decade-away=E2=80=9D technology that might come sooner than mos=
t people realize.=20
(4) New schizophrenia drug could treat Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/76cdde82-4063-43a4-8258-652c16a8574e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Diana Kwon for Nature
Since a schizophrenia drug, the first in decades with an innovative mechani=
sm of action, gained US regulatory approval in September [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/8393bd8f-1967-4878-a54=
d-8d0c4e6b0b1a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], some researchers have proclai=
med a new era for psychiatric medicine [ https://substack.com/redirect/198b=
a29a-952b-424c-b925-c28d82b4f39e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. About half a dozen similar drugs =E2=80=94 for =
schizophrenia, Alzheimer=E2=80=99s disease and other conditions involving t=
he brain =E2=80=94 are in various stages of development, most in early-stag=
e clinical trials.
Back in September, the FDA approved a new schizophrenia drug, KarXT (Cobenf=
y). The approval represented a significant innovation in psychiatric medici=
ne by targeting muscarinic receptors, a mechanism distinct from traditional=
 dopamine-based drugs. Muscarinic receptors are proteins in the brain and b=
ody that respond to the neurotransmitter acetylcholine and play a key role =
in cognition, movement, and other physiological functions. KarXT approval f=
or schizophrenia has renewed interest in targeting muscarinic receptors for=
 other brain conditions, such as Alzheimer=E2=80=99s.
Targeting muscarinic receptors, particularly the M1 subtype, could help tre=
at Alzheimer=E2=80=99s by enhancing acetylcholine signaling, which is cruci=
al for learning and memory. Activation of M1 receptors has been shown to im=
prove cognitive function and may slow neurodegeneration by supporting brain=
 cell communication and reducing the buildup of harmful proteins like beta-=
amyloid and tau. Importantly, this approach would not only treat existing s=
ymptoms of Alzheimer=E2=80=99s but may also address the underlying diseases=
=2E
We=E2=80=99re still pretty long ways away, though. Other muscarinic recepto=
rs drugs have failed to pass through trials. The challenge is due to the di=
fficulty of selectively targeting specific receptor subtypes (like M1) with=
out causing widespread side effects, as these receptors are found throughou=
t the body. That said, the FDA=E2=80=99s approval KarXT  has revitalized co=
nfidence in muscarinic receptor-targeting drugs and their potential for tre=
ating a wide variety of brain-related conditions.
(5) Gary Gensler Announces Resignation from SEC [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/5c6012be-4020-440c-b390-c5309668a112?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
On January 20, 2025 I will be stepping down as @SECGov [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/10825166-05fd-4b08-ab07-d7c0b7a333f2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] Chair.
Packy here. Whew. We knew this was going to happen the second Trump was ele=
cted, but it just feels good to hear him say it, ya know?=20
Gensler=E2=80=99s four-year tenure atop the SEC was defined by his policy o=
f regulation by enforcement =E2=80=94 establishing rules through lawsuits a=
nd penalties instead of guidance =E2=80=94 and overreach. Fittingly, just y=
esterday, a US District Court struck down the SEC=E2=80=99s Dealer Rule [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/27d2e15a-99aa-4aab-90cc-6e2f34428822?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], concluding tha=
t =E2=80=9Cthe SEC exceeded its statutory authority.=E2=80=9D
That all of this is happening while prices soar =E2=80=94 Bitcoin is approa=
ching $100k, Solana just hit an all-time high =E2=80=94 isn=E2=80=99t lost =
on anyone [ https://substack.com/redirect/b7a6588e-e1a8-43f6-a9c0-d461b73ce=
ce5?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. B=
ut =E2=80=9Cnumber go up,=E2=80=9D while very fun, isn=E2=80=99t necessaril=
y optimistic.=20
What I=E2=80=99m most excited about is that, between Gensler=E2=80=99s resi=
gnation, positive momentum behind clear crypto regulation in Congress, and =
price movement, the a16z crypto price-innovation cycle [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/27ad06d0-5edd-4421-8219-66806e681ba8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] will be able to spin smoothly.=
=20
Price =E2=80=94> interest =E2=80=94> developer activity =E2=80=94> companie=
s =E2=80=94> great products.
For the past four years, the cycle got stuck somewhere between companies an=
d great products. Developers got excited, only to discover that the real ve=
rsion of what they were trying to build would land them in court. Now, coup=
led with real improvements in infrastructure (stablecoins, < 1 cent transac=
tion fees, account abstraction, etc=E2=80=A6), I expect to see the price ex=
citement translate into the most compelling suite of crypto products we=E2=
=80=99ve gotten yet.=20
Crypto is already proving its usefulness. Bitcoin is a store of value. Stab=
lecoins are better money infrastructure, as evidenced by Stripe=E2=80=99s $=
1.1 billion acquisition of Bridge. Polymarket played a significant role in =
the 2024 US Presidential election (and got it more right than the media and=
 pollsters). The idea that there are no use cases is dead. Now, the questio=
n is how many really great products will be built this cycle.=20
As I wrote in Blockchains as Platforms [ https://substack.com/redirect/e91c=
2a5d-6c3c-4a76-8c5a-eb82b9e59c49?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], blockchains are platforms with unique benefits =
and real drawbacks, both technical and regulatory. =E2=80=9CWhether a devel=
oper chooses to build their product onchain depends entirely on whether the=
 benefits outweigh the drawbacks for the specific product they=E2=80=99re t=
rying to build.=E2=80=9D As those drawbacks decrease, as building useful th=
ings becomes less likely to land you in jail, more developers will choose t=
o incorporate crypto=E2=80=99s unique benefits into their products.=20
Bubbles are good [ https://substack.com/redirect/6a4f7fef-a846-4287-ab7d-34=
25db442a4b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. Done right, they concentrate talent and resources on big problems and=
 pull the future forward. Gensler was a kink in the bubble machine. I=E2=80=
=99m excited to see what happens now that the machine will be allowed to ru=
n smoothly.
Bonus: AI helps uncover metals in Australia critical for clean energy [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/3062dab0-0ee5-49ab-b496-e4ee8b3d0c35?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Andrew Freedman for Axios
At about 2 kilometers by 2 kilometers, or 1.2 miles by 1.2 miles, Earth AI =
says this expansion could make it one of the largest platinum group [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/06064aa1-912b-4a42-b723-1bd3ef4dd77b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] elements prospects =
globally.
Packy again with an update on our portfolio company, Earth AI [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/ea07073e-bfea-4f84-b6d4-4472c27f5c28?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Since I wrote about the company in April, they=E2=80=99ve continued to dril=
l out their discoveries to validate their size and viability. Yesterday, al=
ong with their partner Legacy Minerals, Earth AI announced [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/741661c6-bf10-48cc-b01e-9a8a4c5b86a6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] that the palladium-platinum=20=
discovery at Fontenoy might be very big. In mining speak: =E2=80=9CAssay re=
sults from the second phase of drilling received have confirmed a large min=
eral system.=E2=80=9D In English: the thickest hit was 360 meters deep, as =
deep as the Empire State Building is tall, and the mineralized area is 2 ki=
lometers by 2 kilometers wide. Fontenoy has the potential to become one of =
the largest projects of its kind on the planet.=20
As an investor, this is exciting news, because if further drills continue t=
o confirm the value of the deposit, it could allow Earth AI to spin its fly=
wheel: sell stakes in the project, put that money into more rigs, drill out=
 more discoveries faster and cheaper. For the world, it=E2=80=99s exciting,=
 because Russia and South Africa are the world=E2=80=99s two largest produc=
ers of palladium, a critical energy transition metal, and Russian exports m=
ay face sanctions. Finding and mining the metals we need in allied countrie=
s is a W.=20
Have a great weekend y=E2=80=99all.
